HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 846
By Reeves
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Kenneth Hollis Choate,
Jr., of Thompson's Station.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Kenneth Hollis Choate,
Jr., of Thompson's Station; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Choate was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Kenneth Choate was born on January 26, 1945, in Houston, Texas; he
graduated from Conroe High School and went on to serve his country with honor and courage
as a captain in the United States Army, 21st Infantry Regiment, during the Vietnam War from
1966 to 1970; and
WHEREAS, he was awarded the Bronze Star Medal with one oak leaf cluster for his
bravery, leadership, and exemplary service to his country; and
WHEREAS, following his military service, Kenneth Choate earned his degree in
veterinary science from Texas A&M University, and he then began working alongside his family,
owning the Conroe Ballroom and later establishing the Frontier Palace, gathering places that
featured top country music artists and various special events; and
WHEREAS, he later moved to Hawaii, where he enjoyed a career as a home builder and
developer alongside his wife, Donna; together, they helped design and build more than 2,200
homes, creating entire communities and touching countless families; and
WHEREAS, Kenneth Choate served as a board member of the National Home Builders
Association, president of the Building Industry Association of Hawaii, and a founding member of
HJR0846
012017
- 1 -

the Building Industry Association Construction Training Center of the Pacific in Honolulu,
Hawaii; and
WHEREAS, deeply devoted to his family, Mr. Choate enjoyed the loving companionship
of his wife of fifty-seven years, Donna Melder Choate, and was the proud father of Kari (Don)
Shepherd and Kelly (Michelle) Choate; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his wife and children, he will be sadly mourned but fondly
remembered by his grandchildren, Keller Shepherd, McKenna Shepherd, Sawyer Shepherd,
Elizabeth Shepherd, Ruby Rae Shepherd, Joshua (Jamie) Choate, Caleb Choate, David
Choate, Jonathan Choate, and Joy Choate; great-grandchildren, Theodore Choate, Charlotte
Choate, Georgiana Choate, and Raphael Choate; and a host of extended family and friends;
and
WHEREAS, he was preceded in death by his parents, Nettie Jane Roberts Choate-
Aldrich and Kenneth Hollis Choate, Sr.; sister, Dolores Jane Feagin; and brother, David Leslie
Choate; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Choate was a faithful follower of Jesus, known for his gentle spirit,
steady kindness, and selfless dedication to helping others; and
WHEREAS, Kenneth Choate leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Kenneth Hollis Choate, Jr., reflecting fondly upon
- 2 - 012017

his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage
and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Choate.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
